  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is the difference between SCORM and xAPI?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "SCORM (Sharable Content Object Reference Model) is the legacy standard for packaging and tracking e-learning content. It tracks basic data like completion status, time spent, and quiz scores, and requires content to run within a browser inside the LMS. xAPI (Experience API, also called Tin Can) is the modern successor that tracks virtually any learning activity — including offline learning, mobile app usage, simulations, and real-world practice — and sends data to a Learning Record Store (LRS). xAPI is more flexible and powerful but requires more technical setup. Most LMS platforms support SCORM 1.2 and 2004; xAPI support is less universal but growing." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Which LMS platforms are SOC 2 compliant?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Enterprise-focused platforms generally maintain SOC 2 Type II compliance: Docebo, Absorb LMS, Skilljar, and TalentLMS all hold active SOC 2 certifications. Among expert-focused platforms, Thinkific maintains enterprise-grade security practices and data protection standards. Kajabi, Teachable, and Podia don't publicly disclose SOC 2 compliance status. If you're selling to enterprise customers or operating in regulated industries, verify SOC 2 compliance directly with the vendor and request their most recent audit report." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "How do LMS platforms handle GDPR compliance?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "GDPR compliance in LMS platforms involves several components: data processing agreements (DPAs) that define how student data is handled, cookie consent mechanisms, the right to data export and deletion (right to be forgotten), data residency options (EU data storage), and breach notification procedures. Thinkific provides GDPR-compliant data handling with DPA availability, data export tools, and student data deletion capabilities. Enterprise platforms like Docebo offer additional features like configurable data retention policies and EU-hosted instances. Always verify GDPR compliance directly with the vendor and have legal counsel review the DPA." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Can I issue accredited certificates through an LMS?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "LMS platforms can issue certificates, but accreditation comes from recognized accrediting bodies, not from the platform itself. Your LMS handles the delivery mechanism — tracking completions, generating certificates, and managing recertification schedules. The accreditation value comes from your organization's relationship with accrediting bodies (like IACET for continuing education, state licensing boards, or professional associations). Thinkific, LearnWorlds, and Docebo all offer robust certificate management. For digital credential verification, platforms like Credly and Accredible integrate with most LMS platforms to issue blockchain-verified badges and certificates." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What compliance features do I need for corporate training?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Corporate compliance training requires: mandatory course assignment with enrollment deadlines, completion tracking with audit trails, automated recertification reminders, digital signatures or acknowledgments for policy training, reporting for regulatory audits (showing who completed what and when), SCORM support for third-party compliance content, and certificate generation with expiration dates. Enterprise platforms like Docebo, Absorb, and TalentLMS are purpose-built for these requirements. Thinkific covers the basics well for expert-led compliance training businesses, while platforms like Kajabi and Podia lack the compliance-specific features that regulated industries demand." } }
    ]
  }
];
